WEBVTT

1
00:00:04.920 --> 00:00:09.459
Lynn-Jones: We have minutes from our March, meeting.

2
00:00:09.700 --> 00:00:12.709
Lynn-Jones: Thanks to Rob.

3
00:00:13.090 --> 00:00:14.309
Lynn-Jones: And,

4
00:00:15.860 --> 00:00:22.540
Lynn-Jones: I, will take a motion to approve them, unless there are some corrections or changes that anyone wants to make.

5
00:00:25.210 --> 00:00:27.100
Ernest Cook: I move that we approve them.

6
00:00:28.370 --> 00:00:30.320
Lynn-Jones: Alright, is there a second?

7
00:00:30.490 --> 00:00:31.280
John Shreffler: Second.

8
00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:32.200
Olivia Fischer Fox: Seconds.

9
00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:34.510
Lynn-Jones: Okay,

10
00:00:35.260 --> 00:00:43.939
Lynn-Jones: All in favor, please raise your, your real hands, not your Zoom hats, so that's, better.

11
00:00:48.580 --> 00:00:53.569
Lynn-Jones: And, any abstentions from people who missed the meeting?

12
00:00:55.060 --> 00:00:57.039
Lynn-Jones: I think I see one there.

13
00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:11.929
Lynn-Jones: So, we will put that down as a 10 to 0 to 1 vote to approve the minutes.

14
00:01:14.570 --> 00:01:23.030
Lynn-Jones: couple of, just, organizational business questions before we get to the political questions.

15
00:01:23.380 --> 00:01:31.779
Lynn-Jones: Even though BU was slow to confirm it, I'm pretty confident that we are having an annual meeting on April 22nd at the Whiteman House.

16
00:01:31.880 --> 00:01:46.680
Lynn-Jones: And, get some more announcements out about, that, and I will select a menu, too, similar to last year's. We have a title for the, talk.

17
00:01:46.860 --> 00:01:50.279
Lynn-Jones: By Carl Zimba. Now.

18
00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:58.679
Lynn-Jones: Carl Zimba's affiliation is that he was commissioned by the Muddy Water Initiative to do a study of the low water levels in the Muddy River.

19
00:01:58.730 --> 00:02:07.280
Lynn-Jones: He has some other affiliations, but they don't really lend themselves to being on the program, because they create some confusion.

20
00:02:07.290 --> 00:02:25.750
Lynn-Jones: But that's who Carl is, and the title, as you see on the agenda, Low Water and High Hopes, Olmsted and the Mudflats in the Muddy River. Because he goes back and looks at Olmstead's design, and why the water level isn't what it used to be.

21
00:02:25.790 --> 00:02:39.430
Lynn-Jones: I had suggested mentioning the Army Corps of Engineers in that title, because they surely deserve some responsibility for the situation that we have in the Muddy River now. But…

22
00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:52.319
Lynn-Jones: we decided that might not be a nice thing to do, so they are no longer mentioned in that title. And we'll try to allow a lot of time for that talk, because I think it's a pretty interesting subject, and he's really done some research.

23
00:02:52.680 --> 00:03:03.319
Lynn-Jones: Deborah has made it possible, or possible very soon, for us to have a new Green Space Alliance map. Do you want to say anything more about

24
00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:05.320
Lynn-Jones: where we are, Deborah.

25
00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:12.690
Deborah Rivers: Well, it went to the printer a little over a week ago, maybe almost getting closer to 2 weeks.

26
00:03:12.910 --> 00:03:29.770
Deborah Rivers: And, I… you and I both reviewed the digital proof, and, so it's… it's a go. I expect it to be delivered no later than the 21st of April, so it will be available for our annual meeting.

27
00:03:31.130 --> 00:03:38.410
Lynn-Jones: Well, thank you for all that you've done with, getting the map updated. I've been,

28
00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:57.680
Lynn-Jones: trying very hard to give away all the old maps before they become totally useless. They're still useful, even though they miss a few maps, but I think the new map will be up-to-date and better, and I hope we have it to distribute at the annual meeting, and

29
00:03:57.680 --> 00:04:11.220
Lynn-Jones: many events thereafter. And thank you for all the work, and, you know, for putting up with my, is that comma in the right place questions, and all of those, you know, interjections as we put this together.

30
00:04:11.290 --> 00:04:12.610
Lynn-Jones: We also have a newer…

31
00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:25.000
Deborah Rivers: Well, and I have to still give Marion some credit, because the whole foundation of the map, I mean, is… it's based on the map that Marion did.

32
00:04:26.500 --> 00:04:38.619
Deborah Rivers: A number of years ago, and so I think she still should get some credit here. And she also helped, in the early part of the process, refining down the properties we were and weren't gonna show, and…

33
00:04:39.420 --> 00:04:42.210
Deborah Rivers: Providing pictures, photos.

34
00:04:43.490 --> 00:04:51.309
Deborah Rivers: And Marion, I have to touch base with you about, what you want to put on the website, because I gotta get that to you.

35
00:04:52.270 --> 00:05:01.960
Lazar Family: I think the credit really goes to Deborah for sticking with this. It was a long haul, and I admire her persistence in doing it.

36
00:05:03.840 --> 00:05:13.090
Lynn-Jones: when we began, I didn't know how we would actually generate the copy, the images that are the map, and Debra made that happen.

37
00:05:13.090 --> 00:05:29.050
Lynn-Jones: and really thought about the layout, the design, and put it together in a very attractive way, and just put it together so it could go to the printer, which is the really key thing. Building on the basic, you know, design, but taking all of the new ingredients

38
00:05:29.050 --> 00:05:42.570
Lynn-Jones: Which got down to, what name will we use for some particular parcels? Because different people call some parks different things, which gets really awkward and political sometimes. But we,

39
00:05:42.570 --> 00:05:49.959
Lynn-Jones: We went with what people usually, you know, call a park, as opposed to what people think it should be called, most of the time.

40
00:05:50.010 --> 00:05:54.219
Lynn-Jones: But it was complicated, even though what you think would be basic.

41
00:05:54.630 --> 00:06:07.100
Lynn-Jones: And, since Marion deserves some credit for this, it's a good time for me to mention that, consistent with the, last, board meeting's discussion.

42
00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:20.409
Lynn-Jones: Marion will be recognized for her long-time contribution to so many different elements of the BGSA's work, including place in the map. And to honor her, we are making a donation to the Emerald Necklace Conservancy.

43
00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:33.670
Lynn-Jones: Instead of, you know, buying a plaque, or a cake, or whatever, contributing to the ENC in Marion's name. And, I think they are already aware of that.

44
00:06:33.880 --> 00:06:44.919
Lynn-Jones: And, consistent with Marion's wishes, I will make a very short speech on this topic at the annual meeting. I promise.

45
00:06:45.520 --> 00:06:46.510
Lynn-Jones: of…

46
00:06:47.630 --> 00:06:55.580
Lynn-Jones: there is a new issue of place, at the printer, or somewhere close to being produced. I look on my doorstep.

47
00:06:55.580 --> 00:06:55.970
Lazar Family: Yeah, baby.

48
00:06:55.970 --> 00:06:58.660
Lynn-Jones: now and again, but I know it's coming.

49
00:07:01.170 --> 00:07:03.889
Lynn-Jones: Do they have a rough estimate?

50
00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:13.010
Lazar Family: I expect it every day. That's all I can say. Unless, you know, I can get after them and find out.

51
00:07:13.140 --> 00:07:16.740
Lazar Family: usually it just shows up sooner than I expect, but.

52
00:07:16.740 --> 00:07:17.350
Lynn-Jones: Nope.

53
00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:18.409
Lazar Family: Who knows?

54
00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:23.609
Lynn-Jones: Well, I, expect it will be available for the annual meeting.

55
00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:25.090
Lazar Family: Sure, it will be.

56
00:07:25.090 --> 00:07:26.840
John Shreffler: That was the plan.

57
00:07:29.260 --> 00:07:35.380
Lynn-Jones: I, will reiterate that I would welcome some assistance

58
00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:49.899
Lynn-Jones: doing some of the important things that we need to do for the Green Space Alliance, particularly communications and getting the, e-update, the, e-newsletter, out every month.

59
00:07:50.000 --> 00:08:04.300
Lynn-Jones: And, you know, I call the e-update a newsletter, some people call place a newsletter, I call Place a magazine. But, you know, different people refer to different things, and sometimes it gets confusing, but that's how I, you know, think about it.

60
00:08:04.350 --> 00:08:06.719
Lynn-Jones: And I just have to say about the e-update.

61
00:08:06.760 --> 00:08:15.860
Lynn-Jones: I went on a walk, regarding Indigenous peoples' sites in Brookline, on, Saturday.

62
00:08:15.860 --> 00:08:26.480
Lynn-Jones: And it was bitterly cold, but there was still a crowd of about 20 people. And about half of them said, oh, I found out about this because of the Green Space Alliance newsletter.

63
00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:45.240
Lynn-Jones: Emily Norton, head of the Charles River Watershed Association, was there with her partner and a lot of other people, and they all said, oh, yes, I look at the newsletter always and come to these events. So someone actually reads it, and they actually, you know, get something out of it, which is a great thing.

64
00:08:46.640 --> 00:09:06.520
Lynn-Jones: And it was a very interesting walk. More on history than green space, but we did spend some time in what is now known as Freedman Park. It has had different names, as part of that, walking tour, as well as the old, burying ground.

65
00:09:06.710 --> 00:09:12.810
Lynn-Jones: Which is, where at least one Indigenous person is, buried.

66
00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:20.960
Lynn-Jones: We don't have to answer this question right away, but I have asked the question. What

67
00:09:21.190 --> 00:09:25.829
Lynn-Jones: should we do to celebrate the Green Space Alliance's anniversary?

68
00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:32.709
Lynn-Jones: And I've had a few, you know, offline discussions about should we do a new edition of Landscapes of Brookline, the book?

69
00:09:32.770 --> 00:09:51.630
Lynn-Jones: Should we raise money? Should we have parties? Should we have an art exhibit? I talked to Michael Berger, who was involved, I think the last time around. I didn't realize until I saw him at what's now Boston College, formerly Pine Manor, that the exhibit actually took place in, their…

70
00:09:51.630 --> 00:10:04.260
Lynn-Jones: I'm not sure what you want to call it, but main room in the former mansion, there. At least, that's how Michael described it. Great place. In fact, I was there for another event.

71
00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:15.850
Lynn-Jones: One big question I have is, should we raise money, and if so, what for? Should we do it for us, or to give something to the town, or some other entity?

72
00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:22.770
Lynn-Jones: So, I don't know how many of you have had a chance to think about this, and it seems awfully early, but if we don't make a plan now.

73
00:10:22.920 --> 00:10:30.329
Lynn-Jones: 2027 is going to start, and that's our anniversary year, and some things require lead time.

74
00:10:31.070 --> 00:10:36.699
Lynn-Jones: Any thoughts at all at this point? We will revisit this question at least once.

75
00:10:42.890 --> 00:11:01.629
Lynn-Jones: Okay, I just wanted to keep it out there. I've, you know, circulated a list, which we probably… we couldn't do everything on that list, probably, but there are ideas that seem appropriate, and I haven't thought of a particular, you know, fundraising target.

76
00:11:01.880 --> 00:11:18.879
Lynn-Jones: I mean, do we raise enough money to endow place in perpetuity, so it's always going to be published and part of the Green Space Alliance mission? Or do we raise money to give the town X number of trees or something else to be planted somewhere?

77
00:11:18.880 --> 00:11:29.110
Lynn-Jones: Or something else. Or do we not raise money at all, and just have parties and celebrations and, you know, publications to honor the 40th anniversary?

78
00:11:30.690 --> 00:11:37.760
Lynn-Jones: Turning to the much more political questions,

79
00:11:37.980 --> 00:11:40.870
Lynn-Jones: Which can be, more difficult.

80
00:11:41.150 --> 00:11:44.340
Lynn-Jones: Even than doing a new map,

81
00:11:44.630 --> 00:11:47.020
Lynn-Jones: There is going to be an override on the ballot.

82
00:11:47.250 --> 00:12:02.520
Lynn-Jones: I don't know how closely you followed it. I sent an analysis of the override and the budget to try to just cover, the main points regarding green space relevant funding.

83
00:12:02.980 --> 00:12:16.459
Lynn-Jones: I don't know if this organization has ever taken a position on an override, but as I understand our 501c3 status, we can. It's not as though we're prohibited from doing it.

84
00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:30.279
Lynn-Jones: There's over $23 million, of which $625,000 is clearly in the, you know, sustainability, parks, and open space budget category.

85
00:12:31.770 --> 00:12:41.550
Lynn-Jones: You know, that's, you know, not a lot, but, some of those particular positions matter a lot. For example, to, Aaron Schute.

86
00:12:41.670 --> 00:12:54.369
Lynn-Jones: And she would love to have them funded, and has made that clear to us privately, before the override question was adopted, and she, like all town employees, cannot really, you know, speak

87
00:12:54.370 --> 00:13:04.420
Lynn-Jones: Out one way or another regarding an override, but in our discussions of budgets for the last couple of years, she has lamented not having that horticultural specialist position.

88
00:13:04.460 --> 00:13:09.059
Lynn-Jones: And not having enough staff to implement the tree preservation by-law.

89
00:13:09.220 --> 00:13:15.429
Lynn-Jones: So… I'm open to any opinions on this. I mean, we could obviously…

90
00:13:15.660 --> 00:13:23.070
Lynn-Jones: Recommend a yes vote, a no vote, or just not take a position and provide information on what's in the override.

91
00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:28.569
Lynn-Jones: Oh, and speaking of information,

92
00:13:28.830 --> 00:13:45.209
Lynn-Jones: we do have the questions, the answers to our questions, now posted, thanks to Marion, on the Green Space Alliance website, and we will call people's attention to those. And I said, you may know who you're going to vote for anyway, but it's interesting to read.

93
00:13:45.210 --> 00:13:49.279
Lynn-Jones: What people say, about those, issues.

94
00:13:49.280 --> 00:14:06.339
Lynn-Jones: And it's interesting to wonder if they thought that they were writing and might get an endorsement from the Green Space Alliance, even though we made it clear we don't. But they're certainly making a pitch, in those, answers to people who are interested in green space.

95
00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:09.289
Lynn-Jones: So, I see, Ernest has a hand up.

96
00:14:09.610 --> 00:14:14.850
Ernest Cook: Hi, Sean, just a question. Do you think if we could raise…

97
00:14:15.370 --> 00:14:21.879
Ernest Cook: Part of the salary of the horticultural specialist that we might be able to convince

98
00:14:22.060 --> 00:14:29.999
Ernest Cook: the town to make it more of a priority. You know, if we put in $25,000 a year or something like that.

99
00:14:31.100 --> 00:14:34.860
Ernest Cook: I mean, I think that would be a great thing to raise money for, for our 40th.

100
00:14:36.790 --> 00:14:43.329
Ernest Cook: But I don't think we could pay for the whole thing for, like, 3 years or something. That would be very expensive.

101
00:14:45.800 --> 00:14:51.050
Lynn-Jones: Yeah, it would… be much more than our annual budget.

102
00:14:52.830 --> 00:14:57.740
Lynn-Jones: Just, you know, even $25,000 would be about 50% of, what we…

103
00:14:57.940 --> 00:14:58.990
Ernest Cook: Yeah, I know.

104
00:15:00.220 --> 00:15:07.050
Lynn-Jones: I don't know, you know, we have this…

105
00:15:07.270 --> 00:15:13.020
Lynn-Jones: precedent that the Sustainability Division's positions are funded by an anonymous donor who gave.

106
00:15:13.630 --> 00:15:18.510
Lynn-Jones: A bunch of money, but that was $750,000 over several years, which is…

107
00:15:18.510 --> 00:15:19.030
Ernest Cook: Right.

108
00:15:19.030 --> 00:15:21.070
Lynn-Jones: Beyond what we would raise.

109
00:15:21.770 --> 00:15:23.029
Ernest Cook: Yes, I bet.

110
00:15:24.710 --> 00:15:29.479
Lynn-Jones: So, but my answer is… I don't know, but,

111
00:15:30.350 --> 00:15:37.619
Lynn-Jones: Okay. It's a lot. It would be a big reach, I think, to… Raise that money.

112
00:15:39.140 --> 00:15:40.250
Lynn-Jones: Antonia!

113
00:15:42.210 --> 00:15:45.060
Antonia Bellalta: If I may.

114
00:15:45.060 --> 00:15:45.710
Lynn-Jones: Certainly.

115
00:15:45.710 --> 00:15:55.210
Antonia Bellalta: I think a question of that has come up in the past, and nonetheless, It's something that is funded

116
00:15:56.420 --> 00:16:04.810
Antonia Bellalta: long-term, I think the town would be pretty skeptical in having it just be a short-term position.

117
00:16:06.570 --> 00:16:17.299
Antonia Bellalta: I think it's a fabulous idea. And then I wanted to talk more about a position on the override. I think it would be very helpful

118
00:16:17.590 --> 00:16:18.590
Antonia Bellalta: if…

119
00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:31.109
Antonia Bellalta: if people don't feel comfortable taking a position, is speaking about why it would affect green space. How, you know, not just

120
00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:40.770
Antonia Bellalta: the urban forestry, but what does that mean to the upkeep of Grieben? So, making a statement about it without saying we support it or don't support it.

121
00:16:41.730 --> 00:16:43.830
Antonia Bellalta: That would be my, my, my…

122
00:16:43.990 --> 00:16:50.209
Antonia Bellalta: I think the more information that people know as to what the budget cut is, what the override

123
00:16:51.490 --> 00:17:07.230
Antonia Bellalta: is going to support, besides schools, that… for Green Space Alliance, you know, and open… because park and rec… recreation gets funded by its own program, so it's more the open spaces and park.

124
00:17:07.390 --> 00:17:11.129
Antonia Bellalta: And, I think DPW, if I'm not…

125
00:17:12.390 --> 00:17:25.400
Antonia Bellalta: misinformed is the one that will be most effective, because there'll be no more maintenance, or there'll be less maintenance, and I think parks need more maintenance right now, and more care.

126
00:17:25.589 --> 00:17:29.880
Antonia Bellalta: So that's a huge… that's a huge, you know…

127
00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:36.319
Antonia Bellalta: But it's a big override, so I'm not sure how, you know, how the community is feeling.

128
00:17:38.310 --> 00:17:47.780
Lynn-Jones: Yeah, there are a lot of different items in it, but in very broad terms, you can say it's mainly for the schools.

129
00:17:48.020 --> 00:17:53.280
Lynn-Jones: There's certainly other funding, but… -Oh.

130
00:17:53.760 --> 00:17:57.000
Antonia Bellalta: But… but we would be effective if it doesn't go…

131
00:17:57.200 --> 00:18:10.569
Antonia Bellalta: the green space would be affected, by just all the things that are getting cut, and what those cuts would mean for Green Space Alliance. I mean, for open space, not green space, but for open space in Brooklyn.

132
00:18:10.850 --> 00:18:16.389
Lynn-Jones: Yeah, the, it's a little bit hard to figure out

133
00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:30.279
Lynn-Jones: how much is cut in a no-override scenario, but the bigger impact is, in a no-override scenario, those five positions, horticultural specialist.

134
00:18:30.360 --> 00:18:45.560
Lynn-Jones: Deputy Director of Sustainability and Natural Resources, and a Program Manager for Sustainability and Natural Resources, and two FTEs to implement the Tree Preservation By-law. Those positions are not funded if the override fails.

135
00:18:45.920 --> 00:18:46.590
Antonia Bellalta: Richard.

136
00:18:47.170 --> 00:18:49.550
Lynn-Jones: The no override scenario.

137
00:18:49.780 --> 00:19:01.779
Lynn-Jones: I think, I think there's one position that DPW loses, regardless of whether the override passes or fails. But it definitely doesn't get those five positions.

138
00:19:01.960 --> 00:19:03.620
Lynn-Jones: If it's voted down.

139
00:19:04.730 --> 00:19:06.340
Lynn-Jones: Deborah?

140
00:19:06.920 --> 00:19:07.489
Antonia Bellalta: Thank you.

141
00:19:07.860 --> 00:19:18.849
Deborah Rivers: Well, I was gonna… Susan just put this in the chat, but I think that's the right approach, is to really point out exactly what Antonia said of what the impact would be.

142
00:19:18.990 --> 00:19:20.300
Deborah Rivers: but not…

143
00:19:20.550 --> 00:19:33.479
Deborah Rivers: you know, so that people understand it's not just about schools. But that would be different than just endorsing it. I think. Would it be… give people an explanation of why it's important?

144
00:19:33.970 --> 00:19:36.970
Deborah Rivers: to, open spaces.

145
00:19:38.950 --> 00:19:39.710
Lynn-Jones: Olivia.

146
00:19:40.600 --> 00:19:48.429
Olivia Fischer Fox: I personally would love to see Brookline Green Space Alliance endorse

147
00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:52.529
Olivia Fischer Fox: The override, because so much…

148
00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:58.839
Olivia Fischer Fox: Has gone into getting the, tree by-law up and running.

149
00:19:59.030 --> 00:20:01.670
Olivia Fischer Fox: Lots of man hours,

150
00:20:02.020 --> 00:20:15.430
Olivia Fischer Fox: as well as sustainability up and running, and to just cut it, it seems like such a waste. When we've made progress, then to take… take it all away is really gonna set Brookline back.

151
00:20:17.580 --> 00:20:22.840
Olivia Fischer Fox: I've just heard from Aaron… I mean, Aaron's pleading to get…

152
00:20:23.500 --> 00:20:29.290
Olivia Fischer Fox: the community to understand that. So, anything we can do to support

153
00:20:29.620 --> 00:20:43.150
Olivia Fischer Fox: Aaron and DPW and all the hard work that staff has done, I think it's imperative to try and put our best foot forward here, personally. Now, I understand everybody's situation is different, but it would be interesting to

154
00:20:43.270 --> 00:20:47.080
Olivia Fischer Fox: To hear from the group, if people are comfortable endorsing.

155
00:20:47.570 --> 00:20:48.810
Olivia Fischer Fox: I would be.

156
00:20:49.520 --> 00:21:05.550
Lynn-Jones: And I will say, just, you know, in the interest of full disclosure, I am on record as personally endorsing this override. I'm listed, along with other people, and I have not in any time

157
00:21:05.550 --> 00:21:23.210
Lynn-Jones: mentioned my affiliation with the Green Space Alliance, when I've recorded a video for override supporters. I'm not sure what they're going to do with that, and when I've given them my name, I think they're listed as a town meeting member from Precinct 1, and, I have not, you know, mentioned

158
00:21:23.210 --> 00:21:38.270
Lynn-Jones: the affiliation. And I will say, again, it's very important not to make a pitch for the override that says town staff like Aaron Schute support it, because that's been a controversy in the past, when it looks as though

159
00:21:38.270 --> 00:21:56.350
Lynn-Jones: town funds are being used in any way as part of a pro-override campaign. This, you know, can be… can set off a backlash and complaints and muddy the waters, so to speak, with, you know… and I don't think anyone's doing that, but if…

160
00:21:56.350 --> 00:22:02.509
Lynn-Jones: You were to say, you know, publicly, we should do this because Aaron Schutez says we really need the money.

161
00:22:02.510 --> 00:22:09.700
Lynn-Jones: It could come back and be used as an example of how town employees are abusing their position.

162
